AB  - Climate change has continuously affected the agricultural sector of ethnic minority farmers in remote areas. This paper examines how climate change affects the agricultural sector of ethnic minority farmers and their adaptation and tries to determine the factors affecting farmers' adoption of adaptation strategies to cope with the impacts of CC in Bac Kan Province, Vietnam. We used survey and FGDs methods to gather data from 362 randomly selected farmers. Multivariate probit regression was applied to investigate the factors that affect farmers' selection of adaptation options. Results show that CC led to a decrease in crop yield, more livestock mortality and negatively affected farmers' health. Farmers have adopted many adaptation strategies to tackle the impacts of CC such as improved crops, change in fertiliser use, using local crops, taking loans, crop diversification and migration. Moreover, education, forestland, amount of loans, access to credit and farmers' health strongly affected farmers' adoption of the adaptation strategies. Our findings enrich the understanding of the impacts of climate change on ethnic minority people in the remote regions and the factors affecting farmers' climate change adaptation strategies and providing the evidence for policy makers, agricultural stakeholders to create the adaptation policies for ethnic minority people in the future.
