TI  - Vulnerability of smallholder vegetable farmers to climate variability in Bosome Freho, Ghana
T2  - AGROECOLOGY AND SUSTAINABLE FOOD SYSTEMS
LA  - English
KW  - Vegetable production
KW  - vulnerability
KW  - climate variability
KW  - Ghana
KW  - MANAGEMENT
AB  - Vegetable farming is a key source of income and nutrition for households in Ghana; however, it faces increasing risks due to climate variability. Understanding farmers' vulnerability is essential for designing effective adaptation strategies. This study assessed the vulnerability of smallholder vegetable farmers to climate variability in the Bosome Freho District, Ghana. Using household surveys (n = 150) and three focus group discussions, we assessed rainfall and temperature trends from 2000 to 2022 with the Mann-Kendall trend test and assessed the smallholder vegetable farmers' vulnerability using the Livelihood Vulnerability Index-Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (LVI-IPCC) framework. The Mann-Kendall trend test revealed a decline in rainfall (p > 0.05) and a significant increase in temperature (p < 0.05). Farmers observed these changes, with 85% noting reduced rainfall and 89% reporting higher temperatures. Adaptation strategies included creating ridges and channels (77%) and cultivating vegetables in elevated areas (74%). The LVI-IPCC framework indicated low overall vulnerability, with Adeito being the most vulnerable. Policymakers are advised to monitor and update the vulnerability index to prioritize and support the most affected communities. The findings underscore the need for targeted government interventions, improved meteorological services, and support for adaptive practices to strengthen farmers' resilience to climate variability.
